Yes -- this is a real strategic issue, not a small implementation detail.

If Beast stays too ONNX-first, you inherit a big ecosystem mismatch: ComfyUI explicitly supports loading ckpt and safetensors files, including standalone diffusion models, VAEs, and CLIP models, while the broader diffusion ecosystem treats safetensors as the common format.  ￼

My blunt read:

onnx = good backend
onnx = bad primary model ecosystem

That is the pain you are feeling.

what ComfyUI uses

ComfyUI’s own repo says it can load:
	•	all-in-one checkpoints
	•	safetensors
	•	standalone diffusion models
	•	VAEs
	•	CLIP models
	•	LoRAs and related variants.  ￼

That is a huge practical advantage because it matches how people actually download and share models.

why ONNX feels limiting

ONNX is excellent when you want:
	•	a portable graph
	•	a runtime target
	•	tighter deployment control

But the public generative model ecosystem is not centered on ONNX. ONNX’s model zoo exists, but it is a curated repository and not remotely the same kind of living, messy, creator-heavy distribution world as Civitai / Comfy-style checkpoint ecosystems.  ￼

So Beast has two different needs:

model ecosystem compatibility
runtime execution control

ONNX helps mostly with the second.

better Beast direction

I think Beast should treat backend and model format as separate layers.

Something like:

model artifact
→ loader / adapter
→ runtime backend

Where model artifact may be:
	•	safetensors
	•	checkpoint
	•	split UNet / VAE / CLIP files
	•	ONNX bundle later

And runtime backend may be:
	•	PyTorch
	•	ONNX Runtime
	•	TensorRT
	•	later Beast-controlled kernels

That is much closer to how the real world works.

recommended architecture

1. native import support for common model artifacts

Beast should import and register:
	•	safetensors
	•	split model pieces
	•	LoRAs
	•	VAE files
	•	text encoder files

This is what will remove the "major pain point" of conversion before use.

2. backend adapters

Then Beast decides how to execute:
	•	direct PyTorch path for maximum compatibility
	•	ONNX path for deployment / control / experiments
	•	TensorRT path for NVIDIA speed
	•	maybe OpenVINO / CoreML later where useful

3. runtime bundle resolution

Given a generator, Beast resolves:
	•	which model pieces are needed
	•	whether they exist in compatible form
	•	which backend can run them
	•	whether conversion is optional, recommended, or required

That is much better than:

everything must become onnx first

practical conclusion

For Beast to feel like a real workbench, it probably needs to say:

drop in common model files first
optimize / convert later if wanted

That is what users expect after living in Comfy land.

what I would not do

I would not make ONNX the only "blessed" import path.

That would give you:
	•	cleaner control
	•	much smaller model universe
	•	more friction
	•	fewer fun experiments
	•	worse adoption

And it puts Beast at odds with where the actual creator ecosystem lives today. ComfyUI’s support for safetensors and standalone components is a big part of why people can move fast with it.  ￼

best Beast framing

formats are not backends
models are not runtimes

That distinction is probably the key design law here.

my recommendation

Short version:

support common safetensors-first model artifacts
treat onnx as one backend path
keep pytorch path for ecosystem compatibility

That feels much more Beast.

